{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491394","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491394"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:45:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:45:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"930"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/930"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.11,0.3,0.09,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90508"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/930"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74748"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"575"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35381"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90508"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man with type 1 diabetes mellitus is referred for an ophthalmological assessment of of his eye disease. He has notice a gradual deterioration in his vision over the last four months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis visual acuity in both eyes is 6/36 corrected and his intra-ocular pressures are within normal range. Dilated fundus examination shows no abnormalities of the macula but there are peripheral cotton wool spots, venous beading and multiple microaneurysms bilaterally. Examination of the right eye anterior segment is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Panretinal photocoagulation","Topical atropine and prednefrin  forte drops","Phacoemulsification","Anterior chamber paracentesis","Penetrating keratoplasty"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe image above demonstrates rubeosis iridis, also known as neovascularisation of the iris (NVI), whereby abnormal blood vessels are formed on the surface of the iris. This form of neovascularisation is the result of dysregulation of pro-angiogenic and anti-angiogenic factors in the setting of posterior segment ischaemia, tumours, ocular inflammation and/or chronic retinal detachments. The photograph shows an inflamed ischaemic eye with significant cataract and eversion of the pigment layer around the pupillary margin (ectropion uveae) indicating chronicity of his ischaemic damage from his advanced diabetes. Without any form of treatment, he would go blind if not treated promptly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most common causes of NVI include diabetic retinopathy and central retinal vein occlusion. Without prompt treatment, it can lead to neovascular glaucoma due to acute angle-closure by vessels. The most appropriate initial treatment for NVI is \u003Cstrong\u003Epanretinal photocoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E \u2013 a form of photocoagulative laser therapy destroying peripheral ischaemic retina to reduce ischaemic drive and therefore reduce progression of NVI. Intravitreal anti-VEGF is also used as an adjunct to antagonise pro-angiogenic VEGF.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neovascularisation of the iris should be treated initially with panretinal photocoagulation"],"references":["Gale MJ, Scruggs BA, Flaxel CJ. Diabetic eye disease: A review of screening and management 